    {
        "content": "<p>Seems like adding multiseries requires comparing the real-valued exponents. Does anyone know how this is being done?</p>",
        "id": 568822623,
        "sender_full_name": "Thomas Browning",
        "timestamp": 1768834912
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>There is an open PR for this work, see <a href=\"https://github.com/leanprover-community/mathlib4/pull/28291\">#28291</a></p>",
        "id": 568826875,
        "sender_full_name": "Jireh Loreaux",
        "timestamp": 1768836139
    },
    {
        "content": "<p><span class=\"user-mention silent\" data-user-id=\"253861\">Thomas Browning</span> <a href=\"#narrow/channel/557175-Lean-Together-2026/topic/Vasilii.20Nesterov.20-.20Verified.20computation.20of.20real.20asymptotics/near/568822623\">said</a>:</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p>Seems like adding multiseries requires comparing the real-valued exponents. Does anyone know how this is being done?</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>Yes, the tactic uses a \"zero oracle,\" which is an arbitrary meta-program that takes an expression <code>x</code> representing a real number and returns a proof of <code>x ? 0</code>, where <code>?</code> may be <code>=</code>, <code>&lt;</code>, or <code>&gt;</code>. Currently, I use a combination of the <code>simp</code>, <code>norm_num</code>, <code>linarith</code>, and <code>positivity</code> tactics, but this part of the tactic is completely modular, so it can be replaced with something else (I'm thinking about trying new interval arithmetic tactics here). You can see the actual code <a href=\"https://github.com/leanprover-community/mathlib4/pull/28291/files#diff-4b04b3d9576ffdec9171bf8000a4925ce89bc5d3b74afecb5bd7460bdc514605\">here</a>.</p>\n<p>If the zero oracle fails, then <code>compute_asympotics</code> also fails  with a message like \"cannot compare x with zero, please add a <code>have</code> statement before the  <code>compute_asympotics</code> call\".</p>",
        "id": 568862879,
        "sender_full_name": "Vasilii Nesterov",
        "timestamp": 1768848346
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Slides: <a href=\"/user_uploads/3121/GImETRdvzqQJpxSjg5YSjgkP/LT_2026_compute_asymptotics.pdf\">LT_2026_compute_asymptotics.pdf</a></p>",
        "id": 568864067,
        "sender_full_name": "Vasilii Nesterov",
        "timestamp": 1768848790
    },
    {
        "content": "<p><span class=\"user-mention silent\" data-user-id=\"552388\">Vasilii Nesterov</span> <a href=\"#narrow/channel/557175-Lean-Together-2026/topic/Vasilii.20Nesterov.20-.20Verified.20computation.20of.20real.20asymptotics/near/568862879\">said</a>:</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p><code>x ? 0</code>, where <code>?</code> may be <code>=</code>, <code>&lt;</code>, or <code>&gt;</code></p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>C++/PHP/Perl use the notation <code>x &lt;=&gt; 0</code>, the <a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Three-way_comparison\">Spaceship operator</a> <span aria-label=\"flying saucer\" class=\"emoji emoji-1f6f8\" role=\"img\" title=\"flying saucer\">:flying_saucer:</span></p>",
